--------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 1-2 DATA PACKS (club, historical)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

openfootball/football.json — CC0-1.0 (public domain dedication).
Source: https://github.com/openfootball/football.json

One pack per league, all pinned to the same upstream commit: English Premier
League (packs/openfootball-eng-pl), La Liga (packs/openfootball-esp-ll),
Bundesliga (packs/openfootball-deu-bl), Serie A (packs/openfootball-ita-sa),
and Ligue 1 (packs/openfootball-fra-l1). The exact upstream commit, retrieval
timestamp, filenames, and SHA-256 digests are recorded in each pack's
manifest.json; a copy of the CC0 1.0 legal text is vendored beside the data.
Coverage is historical completed seasons only, gated per league by
docs/handoff/openfootball-audit.md.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
WORLD CUP FIXTURE / KICKOFF CO-SOURCE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

openfootball/worldcup.json — CC0-1.0 (public domain dedication).
Source: https://github.com/openfootball/worldcup.json

The refreshed internationals pack carries the scheduled World Cup fixtures
martj42 has not published yet, plus exact kickoff times, sourced from
worldcup.json. It is a fixture/kickoff co-source only: martj42 remains the sole
model-training source, completed results are cross-checked against martj42 (the
build fails closed on any disagreement), and the exact commit, retrieval time,
filenames, and SHA-256 digests are recorded under `co_sources` in the pack's
manifest.json. A copy of the CC0 1.0 legal text is vendored beside the data.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
OPTIONAL OPENLIGADB COMMUNITY OVERLAY (NOT BUNDLED)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

OpenLigaDB API data — Open Database License (ODbL) 1.0.
Source: https://www.openligadb.de/
License: https://www.openligadb.de/lizenz

Datenquelle: OpenLigaDB (www.openligadb.de) — Open Database License (ODbL)
v1.0. Golavo ships only an opt-in adapter and disclosure. No OpenLigaDB API
response or derived database is bundled in Golavo. If enabled by a user, raw
responses and the display-only adapted SQLite database remain in a separate
per-user Application Support overlay and can be deleted independently. They do
not enter the CC0 index, forecasts, training, calibration, settlement or exports.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
HISTORICAL TEAM RESEARCH PACK
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Pappalardo/Wyscout public soccer event dataset — CC-BY-4.0.
Source: https://figshare.com/collections/Soccer_match_event_dataset/4415000

Event data: Pappalardo et al., Scientific Data 6:236 (2019), CC BY
4.0 (collected by Wyscout). Golavo modifies the source into seven compact,
competition-and-era team summaries. The pack covers 1,941 matches and
3,251,294 events; raw events and player identities are not redistributed.
These historical aggregates never enter model training, forecasts, or
simulations. Exact source and derived hashes plus the modification notice live
in packs/pappalardo-wyscout-research-2019.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
REJECTED DEPENDENCIES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Golavo does not bundle or add adapters for Transfermarkt-derived Kaggle data,
DataHub football mirrors, Understat, FBref, Sofascore, FotMob, unofficial FPL
endpoints, European Soccer DB, or eatpizzanot. Downstream CC0/PDDL labels do not
cure upstream ToS or database-provenance problems.

Wikidata, weather sources, Football-Data.org, and API-Football are not current
dependencies. OpenLigaDB is optional, keyless, ODbL-isolated and off by default;
its response data is never a bundled dependency.

Golavo is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or sponsored by FIFA, UEFA, any
league, club, or competition organizer. Competition names are used factually
(nominatively) to identify matches. No official logos, emblems, mascots,
trophy imagery, crests, or kit designs are used.
